{"text": "Death and Taxes is a narrative driven, existential, philosophical adventure game. Sounds a bit weird right? It is! We are the Grim Reaper (or one of them), a being brought into existence purely to work in an office stamping paperwork which decides who lives or dies. With fate (and his kitty) as our overseer, we're given instructions on how to make our choices. You don't have to follow what the paperwork says though, you can read through the files of the doomed and make your own decisions on who lives or dies and try to manipulate the outcome. Every time you choose, whether you follow the instructions or not, it affects the world in some way, which we find out from messages on our desk phone. Bit by bit as you choose to slaughter or save, the world can be brought into apocalyptic ruin, or shown salvation. At the end of each day you go have a little chat with Fate, whose conversations get deeper and deeper until you're down a rabbit hole of moral philosophy and existentialism. Except for the period when you're reporting to the cat as Fate goes on holiday, then the conversations are a little bit more simple. Mine were mostly listening to the desperate squeaks of a toy mouse I'd given the cat as a gift, being tortured for eternity as it was imbued with an actual soul. Whoops. You get paid for your hard days work and you can spend that pay in a shop full of booty, manned by a pirate with many a tall tale to tell. These items are either cosmetics to unlock new outfits or widgets that you can place on your desk and play with, but some do special things that will help you and I won't spoil anything any further by talking about them as a lot of the fun is just buying these oddities and finding out what they do. The humour is dry, but constant. Unlike \"Papers, please\" which seems similar on the surface, Death and Taxes isn't really depressing at all, because there's no gritty realism. Morality is discussed in the abstract, we never care much about the people we're killing. I liked that a lot, because I'm quite depressed enough without video games adding to it. Choices are strong, the narrative changes and if you do happen to accidentally bring down the end of the world (my bad), you do get to reset and try again and you'll make different choices, as well as having more knowledge and understanding, so there is a reasonable chunk of replayability here. A single playthrough is less than two hours, but this is definitely one of the few games where I'd love to get all the achievements and figure out all the endings.  Charming, addictive, funny and thought-provoking. Death and Taxes gets a big thumbs up from me! ðŸ’– If you find the reviews of an old Welsh lady interesting, please follow   . ðŸ’–", "appid": "1166290", "steamid": "profiles/76561198018483984", "voted_up": true, "votes_up": "54", "votes_funny": "1", "early_access": false, "tstamp_created": 1582804800.0}
