{"text": "Like a flawed masterpiece, I Am Alive delivers a fantastic post-apocalyptic experience. Set in the fictional town of Haventon, a catastrophic series of earthquakes, followed by the advent of a thick ash cloud that took the name of \"the Event\", have left the whole place in chaos and it is up to the nameless protagonist to go and search for his missing family, one year later. Anticipating The Last of Us's release by roughly a year, this game tried to create the former's depressing and realistic atmosphere, while combining it with Prince of Persia's parkour platforming, succeeding in some areas and failing in other. Where it did shine were its brilliantly executed ideas for survival mechanics: you get two bars in order to play, one for stamina and one for health, the former used for climbing and the latter for fighting. That means that whenever you had to climb somewhere you had to take your stamina into account or risk falling and, accordingly, watch out for your health too or risk dying. The realism and immersion it created was incredible, for the first time in my video game experience the supplies and ammunition were really scarce and you had to make really good use of them in order to survive. There were various types of food and beverages, which respectively raised your stamina or your health and at the same time only 4 types of weapons were available: a machete, a pistol, a bow with reusable arrows and a rare shotgun with only 5 shells in all of the game! To balance the scarcity of weapons, you have the possibility to scare your enemies with your gun, even if it is empty! I found that an incredible idea, to use the psychological factor in battle, can't remember a game using it so effectively to avoid actual combat. There was a nice variety of enemies too, from machete or gun wielding foes to armored vest ones and I particularly appreciated the fact that there were no zombies in it. To spice things up, you also get to make moral choices, in the form of helping some victims along the way, by providing them some of your supplies. Also, despite not being exactly open world, there was some liberty in moving and climbing in some city areas where you had to avoid a huge ash cloud that drains your stamina. The soundtrack was very decent: haunting and tense where it needed to be, especially when running out of stamina. That said, despite these excellently thought ideas, the game falls short in other areas, namely the fact that the protagonist is nameless and not totally easy to relate to (at least he's not mute) and you can add to that a creepy young girl NPC, who you get to carry many times. The checkpoints were scarce too, making it frustrating, sometimes, when you lost. It also made an attempt at adding stealth mechanics, but ended up being pseudo-stealth, at best. Overall game also felt incomplete and low budget at times, especially in the ending, which I will not spoil. It's like, if The Last of Us was a big budget horror movie, I Am Alive would be a smaller and more cult one, like The Road, for those that have seen it. Despite all that, even taking these factors into account, I appreciated what the game tried to accomplish and even the rushed ending, taken with a grain of salt, helped in the creation of this very realistic, tense and immersive atmosphere, which felt unlike most similar games I have played. It reminded me very much of Cryostasis, a game unfortunately not available anymore on steam, that, too, had a fantastic feel, but, due to some flaws, remained mostly unknown. And just because of that, in hope that similar efforts will be encouraged in the future, the game gets a recommendation from me.", "appid": "214250", "steamid": "profiles/76561198039103570", "voted_up": true, "votes_up": "16", "votes_funny": "1", "early_access": false, "tstamp_created": 1551096000.0}
