{"text": "I first played Assassinâ€™s Creed Brotherhood when I was around 11 or 12, so coming into this game again in 2020 was a huge nostalgia trip for me. Exploring Rome sent me right back to my childhood. After finally finishing the game, I remember why I loved it so much.  + The story is brilliant, on par with its predecessor, and the cast of characters, old and new, hold their own and enhance the quality of the narrative. Ezio is more the wiser in this entry and is without a doubt the best character in it. The antagonists are really good as well! + The outside animus story is really good as well. Being able to explore Monteriggioni in modern day as well as having conversations with the characters was one of my main childhood memories of this game. Still holds up.   + The combat feels a lot more fast paced in comparison to previous entries. You can now chain executions after completing a successful execution. This can also be done with a successful counter. Whilst doing this you have to constantly be aware of your surroundings and be aware of interruptions. Itâ€™s quite entertaining, and it looks really cool. + The crossbow is a brilliant addition to the game. I normally despise crossbows in video games, but Brotherhood got it perfectly. Itâ€™s easy to use and itâ€™s incredibly effective.  + The ability to call in other assassins to support in combat is one of the best aspects of this game, and itâ€™s what makes it stand out in the franchise. As you progress, the Brotherhood becomes more and more established as new recruits are added. You can also send them on missions across Europe which level them up and provide you with items and money.  + The climbing hasnâ€™t seen much changes, but there are a couple of minor changes and additions that have been made. Itâ€™s now easier to jump onto ledges that are parallel to you, and the lifts make it easier for vertical traversing. Other than that, itâ€™s still good. + There is a very noticeable visual upgrade from the previous entry, especially in the character models. Thereâ€™s much more detail and focus. The level design is fantastic as always. You spend the majority of the game in Rome, and it is a brilliant place to explore.  +  As well as the main story, there are other things you can do. AC: Brotherhood is the first entry in the series to have proper distinct side quests. Theyâ€™re nothing major, but theyâ€™re unique. There are also other story lines to follow such as The Followers of Romulus and learning about Ezioâ€™s ex-lover, all of which are very interesting. + Once again, the music for this game is fantastic. Iconic tracks from AC 2 have returned, along with some iconic new tracks that help immerse you into the world. Jesper Kyd is seriously fantastic. - The ending. Assassinâ€™s Creed isnâ€™t really known for having really good endings, and this game is no exception. My problem with it is that it didnâ€™t make much sense to me. It felt way too abrupt. My opinion of this might change as I continue my playthrough of the franchise, but at the moment, Iâ€™m just confused.  - The bugs. Oh, the wonderful bugs. There arenâ€™t loads, but there are a few. Climbing can be a nightmare sometimes. Youâ€™ll want to do one thing, but Ezio will want to do another, so there will be times where youâ€™ll have to find a compromise. Thereâ€™s also a game breaking bug near the end where a crucial cutscene wonâ€™t play. Oddly enough, this was fixed by turning V-Sync on. Donâ€™t ask howâ€¦ - The air tackle mechanic is stupid and pointless. There were so many times where I wanted to hang off a ledge, but instead Ezio would just jump on top of somebody, forcing me to climb again. It does more harm than good. Assassinâ€™s Creed Brotherhood was the second game I played in the AC franchise, the first being Revelations. It is without a doubt, one of the best games the franchise has to offer. It is the definitive Assassinâ€™s Creed experience in my opinion. Being able to establish and manage the brotherhood of assassins only reinforces it. Iâ€™ve seen people call Brotherhood â€œan expansion to AC2â€ or just simply â€œa big DLCâ€, and I couldnâ€™t disagree with this statement more. There is more content in Brotherhood, and the mechanics are more refined. I honestly think itâ€™s slightly better than its predecessor. Only slightly. Although I was taken off guard by the abruptness of the ending, the past games so far have had abrupt endings, so I canâ€™t say I was hugely annoyed by it. At the end of the day, questions usually get answered. Same thing goes for the bugs. Theyâ€™re there, but they are manageable. At the moment, Brotherhood stands as my favourite in the franchise. This may change as I replay Revelations, but Brotherhood is something special. Itâ€™s less about a characterâ€™s journey, and more about something greater. The staple of the franchise. The Brotherhood itself.", "appid": "48190", "steamid": "profiles/76561198091255120", "voted_up": true, "votes_up": "66", "votes_funny": 0, "early_access": false, "tstamp_created": 1597579200.0}
