{"text": "LOGistICAL is a great, great game. It truly is, and the way it combines pure logical puzzles with fleet management is both unique and brilliant. LOGistICAL: British Isles is a huge stand-alone extension tot he game, giving you the entirety of the UK, plus Eire and the Channel Isles, to deliver to. The basic set up is this: Every town and borough is represented, and every town's citizens have their own needs. You start out with an old banger of a truck, and you order that truck to drive to town B to deliver what town A wants. When you complete the delivery, you get money, so you can buy bigger, better trucks and go about appeasing the population of the entire country, one town at a time. Here's the basic game flow as an example: Town A wants apples. Town B has an orchard, which means the town produces apples as a resource. Town C has fertilizer, which the orchard needs to produce apples. You take the fuel (fertilizer) to the industry (orchard) and wait for it to make the product (apples), at which point you can deliver the apples to town A. Your truck will automatically go back and forth, until the number of apples the town needs is met, at which point the town becomes 'completed', and it's icon on the map goes from black and white to coloured, to reflect that. From now on, the town will never need another delivery. So that's the puzzle side of things. The management side of the game comes from how and when you work on the towns. You see, until a town is completed it will consume the resources you provide it, and so you have to make sure you're assigning enough trucks and over not too great a distance to meet the demand, and finish the town. L: BI features over two-thousand towns to complete, and has dozens of industries like the one I give an example of above, and many require multiple ingredients to complete. To compound the difficulty, there are also roads which will need to be repaired to be able to be used, and quarantine roads which don't allow the transfer of restricted goods via them. And now the inevitable caveat: for everything the game does brilliantly, it obfuscates and behaves obtusely about something else. Even with the tutorial island included in the game (The Isle of Man), I remained mystified about changing game speed (which comes after completing capital cities) and unlocking industries to build manually (upgrade an existing industry to level three to get to these). The UI is absolutely awful. Even the old, original version of Transport Tycoon was more intuitive and friendly â€“ here, everything is in hovering windows with nonsensical icons, with occasional other markers popping up now and then. Some things are just badly labelled: A truck action, 'skip', actually means set off now, even if it doesn't have a full hold of whatever it is it's going to deliver. Not, as I thought, skip the next destination in the chain. There is a small icon in the bottom right corner of the screen which give you instant tool-tips on everything, but it's still an obscure game to get into. I owned it for a couple of months, and it's only now I've really started to get the fabled 'one more town' feeling LOGistICAL fans crave. Regardless of the UI, once you've learned it, it sticks. The game also integrates seamlessly with the base game, which features the entirety of Australia and has very full, satisfying DLC to bolster it's longevity, into the hundreds of hours. You can currently deliver goods to the entirety of Australia, New Zealand, California, Germany, The Netherlands, Hawaii, Egypt... The end goal is for the whole Earth to be represented, and skipping from one country module to the next is as easy as clicking on the globe and clicking a different country. In summary, LOGistICAL is a fantastic puzzle game with a very addictive management mechanic, and if you spend two or three hours reading a guide and the manual and retrying the tutorial island, you'll end up loving the game and wanting to play it every spare second. ~M~", "appid": "684940", "steamid": "profiles/76561197994097437", "voted_up": true, "votes_up": "5", "votes_funny": 0, "early_access": false, "tstamp_created": 1502280000.0}
