{"text": "was exactly what I was expecting it to be but hoping it wouldnâ€™t! Much like VTM:Bloodlines and Red Embrace: Hollywood (I havenâ€™t played Coteries of New York), you play as a recently turned fledgling whose sire isnâ€™t in the picture. This time you play as Julia, a former investigative journalist who is now the bottom of the barrel in vampire society. Self-loathing, outspoken and a chronic chain smoker. The future doesnâ€™t look bright for this lost soul â€“ well literally because you know, no sun. When a sudden murder needs investigating, Julia is thrown head first into a political game that she is not only unqualified for, but also no one is really willing to help her out. Itâ€™s clear she is a pawn and a disposable one but being the type of person she is, she soldiers on in the hopes of busting this case wide open.   Needless to say, this shares a lot of common ground with other vampire games; newly turned. No sire to guide her. Shouldered with responsibilities far above her status and way too much politics; itâ€™s not exactly original. This version also has a heavy side dose of religion. Nether are things I really enjoy reading. I do however, like being the underdog that no one really suspects. The one everyone takes for granted and doesnâ€™t believe will ever succeed. Extra points for being sassy too.   The artwork is beautifully dark and envisions children of the night quite nicely with itâ€™s gritty, stylish and grungy design. Animated backgrounds and atmospheric sounds/music really push this to the next level as well. As someone who can appreciate the beauty in darkness, this was nice eye candy for my twisted little mind. The cast of eccentric characters was the cherry on the top to this delicious ice-cream Sunday!    Considering Vampire: The Masquerade is in itâ€™s own universe I was a little annoyed when there was mentions of a pandemic that originated from China in 2020 â€“ I mean, really? REALLY? I donâ€™t know about other people but I play 