{"text": "Avoided this game since its' open beta. Then, a few days ago, i decided to take the risk and bought the game for multiplayer, since i didn't like the campaign when i tried the campaign on my friend's computer years ago. > Is multiplayer really dead? I think it is still alive-ish but it might be a regional thing. I'm living in Turkey and game matches me with Central and Eastern Europeans, Russians and sometimes Turks. While most of people aren't recognizable, some of them are regulars and i see them a lot (starting to memorize their names). Please note that nearly all of the game modes are dead. Like in most of the Call of Duty games, the player base shrunk to Team Deathmatch. > Is there a botmatch option? Can i play with bots? Yes, there is botmatch option. In multiplayer, choose custom game (right of the Nazi Zombies, out of the screen) and you're good to go. You can even play War with bots. > Are there cheaters? I think so. In the region i play, some players are suspicious but the situation is not gamebreaking. It's not like they run and hold left mouse button and kill everyone or they kill you from the other side of the map. > COD:WWII borrow some elements from WaW (gamemodes such as War; weapons such as Type 100, PTRS; dismemberment and gore etc.) while trying to modernize the game (and fails in my humble opinion). But in the end, playing CoD: WWII multiplayer feels like playing on a heavily modded, WWII themed custom CoD server. > It also borrow other things from other CoDs. > If you yearn for dark, gritty atmosphere of WaW, forget it. > If you like Pacific theater, forget it. Only thing you can find is some of the Japanese guns. > If you like to play a simple but fun shooter, you won't find it here too. It might be fun in some cases but it is not simple-fun for sure. > Gore isn't that good like in WaW. Most of time you can't even notice if someone lose their limbs. + Some design problems and old-school graphics here and there (which feels extremely cheap) but graphics are good enough. + If you want to play a mindless multiplayer shooter, it makes you play. + Carentan, if you miss the CoD 2 (on store page they say that you have to buy Season Pass to play on Carentan but i didn't buy Season Pass and, for an unknown reason, i can play on there). + You don't need to pay for microtransactions (COD Points). - Overpriced for what it offers. - Overcomplicated, nearly useless menu. - Some weapons are only unlockable with supply drops (loot boxes)(i.e. PTRS). - No dedicated servers. - Most of the guns are identical. Pistols are underpowered. Weird weapons such as Claymore (the sword one). - A lot of so-called features such as HQ (MMO-like hub area for players), weekly and daily challenges (and some of them are impracticable due to dead game modes such as Domination and War), contracts (time-limited challenges, i.e. kill 10 players with shovel in 20 minutes), social ranks (all of them can be gainable in HQ) and in-game currencies like armory credits (to unlock some avatars, player cards, weapons skins and get contracts) and COD Points (to buy suppy drops - it is not necessary though, you get supply drops while playing).   These features somehow makes you play the game but they also drains your energy and desire to continue. Especially contracts are forcing you to play how they want you to play and sometimes it ruins the game not only for you but your teammates since -let's say- you try to melee players in a limited time. You can always pretend if they are not in game but common/rare supply drops or other rewards you get is always tempting. Even if you ignore them, someone else in your team might want to take their chances to complete contracts and ruin your game (i.e. they can kill less and die more in TDM). - I never expected a realistic atmosphere or pure 1940s while i decided to buy the game but the skins and emotes they added ruined the game atmosphere beyond my expectations. Vivid coloured weapon skins, a lot of weapon attachments, weird weapon charms, 90's style dances, ugly player cards and emblems... it feels like an alternative WWII scenario (or a third-party modification). - Uniforms aren't distinguishable. Is that guy an enemy or not? You can't be really sure about it. Furthermore, there are global skins which can be obtainable from supply drops (a.k.a. loot boxes) makes it impossible to say who is who (yes, you can still see color coded nicknames -red and green- but sometimes you can't see them at all or they don't matter). - Auto-balance system is non-existent. Good luck playing 5v2 if something happens. Even if you're in outnumbering side, you'll get bored while searching for enemies. If the game find some other players in background, joined players somewhat fixes the problem but still, teams generally ends up unbalanced. - A little bit grindy to level/rank up, unlock new weapons and perks (with double XP for Soldier, Division and Weapons and it is active since i bought the game -it seems like it is permanent) - TDM-only. \"But you played the game long enough and even found it fun, so why don't you recommend the game?\" you ask. Yes, i played the game for 20+ hours in 8 days and i found it kind of fun. But the multiplayer -especially in this condition- is mediocre at best. If i say otherwise, i would deceive you. I guess i found it fun because i feel tired due to pandemic and other factors and wanted to play a fairly casual multiplayer first person shooter which kind of reminds me older CoD games and end of 2000s and start of the 2010s. So, yes, i'm playing it but it doesn't mean that it is a well-crafted game. So, if you really want to try the multiplayer of the CoD: WWII but can't decide, i hope i could give you some ideas about the multiplayer mode of the game.", "appid": "476620", "steamid": "profiles/76561197981055338", "voted_up": false, "votes_up": "5", "votes_funny": "1", "early_access": false, "tstamp_created": 1600084800.0}
