{"text": "I'm updating my review to accommodate for the changes that came with the cooperative update which, supposedly, is inspired by SWAT 3 & 4. I do have to disclaim that I was banned from the community forums for being \"toxic\" (despite my content being mostly criticisms and feedback about the game), but this is a review of the game itself and not a review of the developer's actions. To kick things off, we're gonna talk about the what the game is about. It's basically Rainbow Six: Siege, without the operator gadgets. It's really standard stuff. Instead of being a unit of elite operators taken from around the globe, you're part of a SWAT team. Keep this in mind later. Now how's the core gameplay? Well the intent of the developers is to provide a \"realistic\" gameplay experience. This \"realistic\" experience isn't really anything special, and is sometimes just laughable. The game features a 3D planning map before every round. This is mostly there to tell you where the hostage or bomb and tells you where you should spawn. It is rarely used for actual planning. This map is also completely negated if you have the map knowledge. The gunplay is horrid, the animations are a mess (this is supposed to be improved on next update, but they didn't actually create it in-house), and the sounds make my ears bleed.  The movement in this game is clunky and sluggish. Speaking of movement, this game also comes with a stamina system to combat running and gunning. And they somehow screwed up the stamina system by making it to that shooting a gun takes a noticeable amount of stamina away. Terrific.  Doors are an important part of mostly every tactical shooter. In order to open doors, you have to press F twice. One for slightly opening it and the other press for fully opening it. There are no faster ways to open a door. You also have to open both doors in a double door in order to get through. Now those were just some of the few problems this game has. Let's talk about the arsenal. Despite being a SWAT team, you're able to carry frag grenades. Grenades in this game are wack. It doesn't feel good throwing them, and the animation of you throwing your gun at them doesn't help. The other gadgets the SWAT team has are flashbangs, NODs, and C2 charges. The NODs don't have autogating so don't expect to be able to see anything but white. The SWAT team also gets access to 4 different weapons. The M4, SCAR, a shotgun, and a shield. The shield counts as a weapon since you one hit everyone with it. The terrorists get access to 2 weapons. A MAC-10 and an MP7. They have access to frags, door wedges, and door traps. The way you deal with door traps is that you shoot the wire, instead of cutting it with pliers like a normal person. Let's talk PvP, the mode that launched with the game initially. There are 3 modes. Hostage, bomb, and TDM. The planning map I mentioned earlier shows you the location of the bomb because you can apparently hear it beeping the next block over. The hostage will show on the map when he's moved because he has a motion activated GPS. You cannot kill the hostage. TDM is self-explanatory. The hitboxes are a mess. You can paint a guy and he won't go down, yet he'll pop your head in a single shot with a pistol. Now let's discuss PvE because that's a beast of its own. The PvE in this game is stated to be inspired by SWAT 3 & 4. This modes adds nothing that made SWAT 3 & 4 fun & immersive. The AI is a pile of hot garbage. Once they hear a noise, they'll all come running towards it like dinner's ready, basically making a funnel of enemies come towards your way. They don't have voices, making them extremely unpredictable and unfair. They'll either be top of the class Navy SEALs with their accuracy or don't even attempt to aim. There is no middle ground. They'll also sometimes do a 360 no scope when you get real close to them. The terrible AI makes it impossible to get past the first level. The map design makes no clear sense whatsoever. Whose idea was it for the terrorists to set traps on basically every door way and set door wedges outside of their place, locking themselves in? I'm beginning to think these guys are extremely suicidal. The PvE features an ROE that you have to strictly follow. It's very hard to strictly follow an ROE when its complete crap. You have the option of \"arresting\" suspects, but that's rarely encouraged, since you can only get a single flashbang and nothing else. Whether something is considered unauthorized or not is unclear. Sometimes I'll kill an oblivious man the next block over and it won't count. Other times, they'll surrender a split second after shooting me and it's counted as unauthorized force. It desperately needs non-lethal equipment, which SWAT 3 & 4 has. Even when someone surrenders, you can't zip tie them, basically making them free to run whenever they want (they choose not to). Overall, this game doesn't have a lot going for it. The last time I checked, the game's population was a measly 5-6 players. This was just some of the many problems this game has. I don't recommend it.", "appid": "1359090", "steamid": "profiles/76561198098423174", "voted_up": false, "votes_up": 0, "votes_funny": 0, "early_access": true, "tstamp_created": 1597233600.0}
