{"text": "Unlike other reviewers, I actually quite enjoyed the color palette and overall visual aesthetic.  I dare say that was my favorite aspect of this rather short and unfortunately cliche detective romp with a pretense of cosmic horror.  The look appeals to my nostalgia both for 80s era games, and the 80s aesthetic in general.  Nonetheless, it did make locating certain key objects on screen challenging without using the feature to show all clickable spots on each location. Unfortunately, the rest of the game's features are mediocre at best.  The character images seem to be all (or at least mostly) stock.  While most more or less fit into the game, there are at least a couple that don't feel like they quite fit the role the developer slotted them into.  To make matters worse, a couple of the stock images are familiar enough that any sense of immersion was lost.  The music is all stock as well. The writing matches the character models perfectly (which is to say it was shallow).  The story was quite linear and cliche, with few twists or surprises, no development of atmosphere, and no depth or poignancy.  The characterizations all were quite one-dimensional.  While none of it was bad, per se, none of it was particularly good or memorable either. Needless to say, the story in this game fails to come close to Lovecraft, and indeed (like so many others) misses the whole point of what makes most of Lovecraft's stories both endearing and horrific.", "appid": "756100", "steamid": "profiles/76561197985319331", "voted_up": false, "votes_up": "6", "votes_funny": 0, "early_access": false, "tstamp_created": 1561809600.0}
