{"text": "I know I'll be against the majority with this review, and I knew beforehand this was going to be a short game before going in. But with barely 4 hours of total playtime Firewatch can hardly be considered a game. It's more of a (very) short interactive story with pleasant visuals. The story isn't that deep or interesting either, it's very linear until the end. In a few  points there were nice hooks, that could have been developed into something interesting, but they were not taken advantage of, resulting in an overall flat and linear story that will leave you nothing after ending. TLDR: Visuals and voice over are quite good. But sadly there isn't much else. Total game length is barely 4 hours. So buy at a big discount, if you must, but it still might feel like overpaying.", "appid": "383870", "steamid": "profiles/76561198082258384", "voted_up": false, "votes_up": "51", "votes_funny": 0, "early_access": false, "tstamp_created": 1534420800.0}
{"text": "My only issue with this game is the terrible matchmaking, which is a big issue. My first few matches were fair, every single one after was me getting my ass kicked by people with fancy skins and exclusive mounts. Out of 5 hours I've only enjoyed my first 20 minutes.", "appid": "504370", "steamid": "profiles/76561198072215182", "voted_up": false, "votes_up": 0, "votes_funny": 0, "early_access": false, "tstamp_created": 1511438400.0}
{"text": "Not an essential expansion and you don't get what is advertised.   Just finished a campaign and a there are a few bugs. All in all, these bugs would have been easy to spot by a rookie QA team. Generally I am underwhelmed and disappointed. Lets take the text that was advertised and compare it to the product that was shipped - shall we? As Nakalim, you have a head start in tech and you'll actually keep it for a very long time, like 100+ turns on normal difficulties, probably some less on higher difficulties. But it does not feel like \"They ... are very poor at Science \". They are very good for most of the game at science thanks to the headstart and the relics. The use of relics for non-tech is meh. Maybe there is a niche use of relics with a production specc-ed hero on a production specc-ed system but is not obvious to me. To gain advantage of the temple you need a very narrow conjunction of circumstances. \"Their relationship with the Academy allows them to gain control over other systems through the Influence of their Temples,\" just means that there is another way to convert pacifically neighbouring systems that are low on influence. Consider that it will not happen on 80% of the playthrough and if it happens, will not tip the balance by much. So very niche, very gimmicky. Temples are not a core mechanism.  Generally the way they play is like Venetians in other 4x games - very hard to colonize due to horrible desert start and no colonization ship at spawn. But thanks to turn 1 access to market  to buy strategic resources and decent dust production, it makes it easy to have 1-2 very good mid game ships early flanked by half-a-dozen mercenary ships by turn 20. Mercenaries will cost you then 20-30 dust per ship upfront and 4 dusts per turn. You can then pass turn 20-50 to expand by attacking neighbours. So yes - these guys play like merchants paying for mercenaries and headhunters with a few own troops backed by strong tech. They do NOT feel at any moment like religious figures on a royal prophecy. That the relics make them so good at science is also very weird to me. I just don't buy that bits of bones and sacred clothes do generate blue science matter, sorry. The best part of the DLC is actually the changes to the academy. The mechanisms are quite well explained in the DLC description and add fun mechanism. That was unexpected but cool. Please note there is no way to interact with the academy by normal standard diplomatic means. You have to get summoned and interact only on their terms. Ok why not.  I was more thumb down than thumb up after all this. But what really nailed it to thumb down for me is... that the main quest of this faction DLC cannot complete on chapter 4. There are two tech to unlock and once they unlock it does not move to next chapter. I am sure it will be fixed soon. but in 2019, the way DLCs are priced - not properly QA the main quest of a faction DLC? This is ... un-ac-cep-ta-ble.  And yes it is also well reported on a few places including their official forums...", "appid": "1128540", "steamid": "profiles/76561198080099141", "voted_up": false, "votes_up": "331", "votes_funny": "9", "early_access": false, "tstamp_created": 1568376000.0}
