{"text": "To be honest, it's a good game... only if you cut-out the \"Assassin's Creed\" part from it. Because this is sure as hell ain't an Assassin's Creed game. You want to make an open-world RPG with fantasy stuff on it? Great, go ahead and do it but for the love of all that is holy,  A lot of stuff doesn't add up. Spoilers ahead, skip to Pros / Cons for a basic review. The Animus   show you different stories / endings - it's just impossible. And there's a simulation inside a simulation which can also show you different stories based on your choices, you just can't do that with the Animus. Ubisoft should've just made a separate RPG game & kept the \"Assassin's Creed\" title far from it but let's poop on that logic, it's gonna generate money! Abstergo is already selling Animus to everyone - so any idiot with a little brain can discover whatever they want, all you need is the DNA of someone. New Animuses / Animi can use the DNA of anyone and is no longer limited to the user's DNA only. So, why the rest of the World doesn't know about The Hidden Ones / Assassins and Templars / Order of the Ancients / Cult of Kosmos / <insert next game's villain group name> ? That broken spear of Leonidas only contained two blood samples? Pretty sure I've killed thousands of enemies with that spear. The protagonist only cuts herself / himself once, there's no way that blood is still on that spear after all this time. From the previous games, we know how powerful and resourceful the modern-day Templars are. Yet once they knew all about freaking   they only sent 3 common soldiers without guns to investigate? Otso Berg killed Layla's best friend in the previous game. Layla has killed several people in the previous game, 3 soldiers in this game and her doctor as well. Yet she let Otso Berg live? Are you serious? He's one of the biggest leaders of the Templar order. And why did he came to Layla alone is beyond me, why is he fighting with a sword? Why not just shoot her and be done with it? Layla's last hit to Otso Berg looks extremely fatal, how on earth did he survive that? Mythical creatures, revisiting realms of afterlife at will, Isu machines speaking in English, enemies performing godly moves and you have godly abilities. Remember when Assassin's Creed used to be historically accurate? The goals of the modern day Assassins and Templars made sense? That franchise died with Desmond Miles. Since when and why are we calling \"Those who came before\" by the name \"Isu\"? The World was saved by Desmond's sacrifice, what's the point of using the Animus now? They're clearly not searching for any artifacts of Eden. The protagonist in the Animus confirms that their power can drain over time, so no point in going through all that trouble with the Animus to find some ancient piece of Eden that may or may not work. The reason why I'm focused more on the modern-day story is because you have to have a good enough reason to be in the Animus in the first place and I don't see any good reason to do that. The modern-day story is a complete mess and it's not going anywhere. Absolutely nothing happens when we finish the main story of the protagonist inside the Animus. We don't discover any artifacts that would help the Assassin in the ongoing battle against the Templars. It has become clear that Ubisoft has no idea what to do with the modern-day story-line and they don't seem to care enough to tie up loose ends. Instead, they're adding more characters to the story that we know nothing about and honestly I don't care about them. I didn't feel anything when Layla's best friend died in the previous game and her doctor's death in this game and one injured character - that's because I don't know much about them to care. Yet when Rebecca was shot a few titles back, I was desperate to see what happens next. I'm interested in finding out what happened to the previous characters such as Rebecca Crane, Shaun Hastings and William Miles. Those characters seemed to have been abandoned. Apart from the stinky poop that is the new modern-day and Isu stuff, the world of Greece is massive and beautiful, though most of the assets are from the previous game. But bigger doesn't always mean better. Maybe some people will like it, maybe some won't have the time to 100% everything. It took me a lot of time to finish up everything in the game but I encountered a bug with an engraving challenge, so I didn't get that satisfying feeling of completing everything because even though all quests, locations have been completed, there's one engraving challenge that's now impossible to complete. Maybe some completionists would know how annoying this can be. I pre-ordered the Ultimate Edition but I was shocked to see the number of premium content that are available for purchase using more money. Micro transactions in a single-player game is awful. I feel like I'm missing out. What's the point of purchasing the most expensive edition if I still have to buy more stuff to get everything the game has to offer? There is a way to get premium items for free but the process is worse than loot-boxes. + Gorgeous graphics and good soundtrack which fits various atmospheres. + Greece is really huge, there's a lot of things you can find that might surprise you. + Land adventures on foot or horse or even mythical creatures (act as cosmetics). + Sea and underwater adventure with customizable ship, its lieutenants and crew. + Tons of customization are available for your character and your preferred play-style. + Very realistic facial expressions, conversations feel natural. + So many quests! So many choices! So many outcomes! So many save slots! + You can bang quite a lot of NPCs without getting any ancient STDs. ! Requires a lot of time to complete everything, then there's the New Game+. ! Assassin's Creed game(?). ! Radiant quests for a never-ending adventure. ! Mythical mounts, ship items, crew can be obtained (they are cosmetics). ! Requires a lot of grinding before moving on to the next story related mission. - Poor modern-day story from the very beginning to the very end. - Uses about half of the game's assets from the previous game. - Isu story-line doesn't make much sense. - So many repetitive quests, even the dialogues of some quests are the same. - Very limited number of sea shanties compared to the previous titles which gets boring. - Mythical armor sets and ship lieutenants that can be purchased are not just cosmetics. - Lacks logic in most situations and basic common sense in some situations. - Micro-transactions in a single-player game. Question: How many Assassin's Creed games will you release before ending the series? Ubisoft:  You have to visit Ubisoft's game booth at every gaming event and play all the games there. What's that? You live in the other side of the World? Well then.. no rewards for you! You have to participate in their Closed Alpha Tests, Open Alpha Tests, Closed Beta Tests, Open Beta Tests of their games. What's that? You weren't selected by them to be a tester? Well then... no rewards for you! You have to own several other Ubisoft games on the same account. What's that? You don't have the money and not interested in those other games? Well then... no rewards for you!", "appid": "812140", "steamid": "profiles/76561198063115240", "voted_up": false, "votes_up": "60", "votes_funny": "37", "early_access": false, "tstamp_created": 1538740800.0}
